Youth Refugee Asylum Trends Across Nations

Author

Dominic George Augustine

Published

April 1, 2025

Imagine a world where millions of children are forced to flee their homes, seeking safety in unfamiliar lands. Iran emerges as the largest host of refugee children under 18, followed closely by Turkey, Pakistan, Uganda, and Germany placing a heavy burden on these nations.

Code 
import polars as pl
from plotnine import *
import geopandas as gpd

df=pl.read_csv("/content/unicef_indicator_1.csv")                               # to Read file

df_2023 = (df.filter(pl.col("year") == 2023))                                   # Filter data for the year 2023

# ---- BAR GRAPH

df_pd = df_2023.to_pandas()                                                     # to convert to pandas

df_pd = df_pd.sort_values(by="obs_value", ascending=False)                      # sorting, makes the graph looks better

bar_chart = (ggplot(df_pd, aes(x="country", y="obs_value"))                     # define x and y axis
    + geom_bar(stat="identity", fill="blue")                                    # assigning blue color
    + scale_x_discrete(limits=df_pd["country"].tolist())                        # Sort x-axis
    + theme_minimal()                                                           # theme select
    + theme(
        axis_text_x=element_text(rotation=90, size=8),                          # Rotate & adjust text size
        figure_size=(15, 6))
    + labs(                                                                     # to add labels
      x="Countries",
      y="Number of Refugees under the age of 18",
      title="Bar Graph of young Refugees in 2023")
)

bar_chart.show()                                                                # display the bar chart

The bar graph starkly illustrates this uneven burdenâwhile a few nations provide refuge to countless displaced children, many others play only a minimal role. As the bars shrink, they serve as a reminder that the responsibility of protecting the worldâs most vulnerable should not rest on the shoulders of a few but be shared by all.

Code 
# ---- WORLD MAP
world = gpd.read_file("https://public.opendatasoft.com/api/explore/v2.1/catalog/datasets/world-administrative-boundaries/exports/shp")
(ggplot()
  + geom_map(world)                                                             # to obtain the world map outline/shape
)
map_df_2023 = (world
  .merge(df.to_pandas(), left_on="name", right_on="country", how="outer")       # to assign the values
)
map_2023 = (ggplot(data=map_df_2023)                                            # to plot the graph
  + aes(fill="obs_value")
  + geom_map()
  + labs(title="World Heat map of Young Refugees in 2023")
  + scale_fill_gradient(low="#FFD700", high="#8B0000")                          # Applied hex values for gold and dark red
  + coord_fixed()
  + theme(
        figure_size=(13, 6))                                                    # resize the map
)
map_2023.show()                                                                 # display the World map

The world map reveals the disparitiesâdarker regions highlight countries hosting the highest numbers of displaced children, with Iran, Turkey, Pakistan, Uganda, and Germany standing at the forefront.

Code 
# ---- TIME SERIES MAP
df_iran = (df
  .filter(pl.col("country").
          is_in(["Iran, Islamic Republic of", "Turkey", "Pakistan", "Uganda", "Germany"]))
)
time_series_plot = (ggplot(df_iran, aes(x="year", y="obs_value", color="country"))  # Create a time series chart
    + geom_line()                                                               # Line plot
    + labs(
        title="Time Series of Young Refugees in 2023",
        x="Year",
        y="Number of Young Refugees"
    )
    + theme_minimal()
    + theme(
        axis_text_x=element_text(rotation=0, size=10),                          # Rotate x-axis labels
        figure_size=(13, 6)                                                     # Increase figure size
    )
)
time_series_plot.show()                                                         # to dispay the graph

The time-series chart tells a more dynamic story, tracking how child welfare indicators shift over time. Policy changes, global crises, and economic growth leave their imprints, shaping the futures of millions.

Code 
# ---- scatter plot with a regression line
scatter_plot = (ggplot(df_2023, aes(x=df_2023.columns[0], y=df_2023.columns[2]))  # Adjust column names
    + geom_point(color="blue")                                                  # Scatter plot points
    + labs(
        title="Scatter plot of Young Refugees in 2023",
        x="Country",
        y="Number of Young Refugees"
    )
    + theme_minimal()
    + theme(
        axis_text_x=element_text(rotation=90, size=8),                          # Rotate x-axis labels for readability
        figure_size=(13, 6)                                                     # Increase figure size
    )
)
scatter_plot.show()                                                             # Display the scatter plot

As we zoom into 2023, the scatter plot with a regression line reveals deeper insightsânations with higher economic stability tend to show better outcomes for children, yet exceptions challenge this trend.

These insights remind us that beyond the numbers are real lives in need of support, urging the global community to step up and share the responsibility.
